<br>
I was in a group today that decided to try to take out a few of the minis in BoT.  Laef, Oreen and Gaukr are all up.  We decide to take out Laef first.<br>
<br>
At this time I get a tell from someone asking if any minis are up.  I tell them that we're about to fight one now.  We engage, win, and decide to move on to Oreen.<br>
<br>
We arrive at Oreen's room and I get a tell from the individual saying they attempted to solo Oreen but failed, and were setting up for another attempt.  I told them that my group was also preparing to attempt to kill Oreen.<br>
<br>
To which I get the response, &quot;You going to steal my camp? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> &quot;<br>
<br>
Well, I wasn't really expecting this response, though maybe I should have, because I didn't really think of what the person had as a &quot;camp&quot;.  It's not as if they were there for hours (or even <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>a</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> hour) clearing PHers.  Seeing that a mob is up, making a run at it and failing, isn't what I ever thought of as a genuine camp.<br>
<br>
I'm not even sure the person is serious at this point, so I just respond, &quot;Heh.&quot;  The person starts talking with others in my group, and she begins making comments about how what we're doing is bad ettiquette, camp stealing, impolite, &quot;not cool&quot;, ect.<br>
<br>
Now, I know the official Sony stance is that camps &quot;don't exist&quot; and that it only matters who engages the mob first.  I also know that there are some unwritten rules of EQ that most players try to respect about not moving in on someone else's &quot;camp&quot;.<br>
<br>
The problem is, I really didn't agree with this individual's view of what constituted a camp, as I mentioned above, and I didn't really think it was right for me to tell my group &quot;Sorry, I've got to leave, because I think we should give this individual an unlimited number of attempts at killing this mob for an indefinite amount of time&quot; while we are there with a fully prepared and clearly capable group that can take out the NPC in question.<br>
<br>
And for that matter, I think it's a bit impolite for an individual to essentially deny such a group an attempt at a NPC where they've already failed and been forced to at least temporarily abandon the camp.  When we got to the camp, in fact, I didn't see the individual in question there, and the people in my group were claiming we had a person there first.  I'm not sure of this fact either way.  I guess it's possible that the individual didn't even make the failed run at Oreen that they claimed, though I don't really believe that they were lying.<br>
<br>
So anyway, my feeling is, neither party is any more &quot;entitled&quot; to the camp or the mob as any other, and that if the individual wants to make another attempt at the mob before us, that's up to them, but that we shouldn't wait forever while they prepare, attempt, possibly fail, and try again.  So I tell the person if they think they can solo Oreen, to go ahead and do it.  Apparently this got the person in a &quot;rush&quot;, made an attempt, and failed.  We then engaged Oreen and defeated him.<br>
<br>
I try to explain my reasoning to the individual, who makes comments like &quot;I thought you were cool&quot;, ect., but my opinion of what constitutes a valid camp is dismissed as &quot;BS&quot;.  I obviously don't think of my opinion as BS, nor is my reasoning behind what constitutes a camp something that I conjured up &quot;on the spot&quot; as justification for my own &quot;greedy&quot; actions.  It's just what I always thought of as common sense... that it's not fair to lay indefinite claim to a camp you're having clear difficulty holding.  That's not something I personally would do.<br>
<br>
I'm willing to accept the fact that I might have been &quot;wrong&quot; here, or as wrong as anybody can be in what is essentially a rather grey area of ettiquette without any clearly defined rules.  I'm curious about whether the &quot;majority opinion&quot; is with me or against me (though I understand that this forum would hardly be capable of producing a true scientific determination of &quot;majority&quot;).<br>
<br>
It bugs me, because apparently in the eyes of this individual, I did something that makes me &quot;worse a person&quot;, when really all I did was attempt to live up to my own personal beliefs about what is right and wrong in such a situation.  I've argued against &quot;taking over camps&quot; at times where I felt another group or individual really did have a true and well established camp, and by and large I try to save the people I interact with as much grief as possible. In this situation, I'm afraid it was a no-win situation... either I cause grief for all my groupmates by abandoning them, or I earn the ire of the person whose camp we &quot;stole&quot; by not respecting the &quot;camp&quot; I don't think they had adequately established.<br>
<br>
It sucks and either way seems to me a pretty good argument to never stepping foot in a zone like BoT again and spending all my time in instanced LDoN zones. ;\ <p>--Velsor<br>
